\textbf{x-intercept}\begin{align*}
f(x)
\end{align*} has an x-intercept when $f(x) = 0$. So

\begin{align*}
0 = \frac{2x^2}{x^2-1}
\end{align*}

Cross multiplying gives $2x^2 = 0$, which simplifies to $x = 0$. So the
x-intercept is $(0,0)$

\textbf{y-intercept}\begin{align*}
f(x)
\end{align*} has an y-intercept when $x = 0$. Plugging
in \emph{x = 0} gives $f(0) = 0$.

So the y-intercept is the same as the x-intercept, $(0,0)$

